## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. This isn't a compile error — it's a **runtime failure**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait for graceful exit, but don't hang forever
            if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
            {
                // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
                // There is NO forced-kill equivalent in .NET 8.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` is gone** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime. Replace with `CancellationToken` — the only supported cooperative cancellation model. |
| **Blocking calls won't cancel** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation has no effect. You **must** convert to async APIs that accept `CancellationToken` (e.g., `Channel<T>.ReadAsync`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync`). |
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no safe equivalent to `Abort()`. If a worker truly hangs, the only escape hatch is `Environment.FailFast()` or process restart. Design all operations to be cancellation-aware. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile` flag can't interrupt blocking calls. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async/await`, `WaitHandle`, and `Linked` sources. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` pattern** | Delete entirely — no replacement needed. `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception; `finally` blocks always run. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` for timing** | Replace with `await Task.Delay(timeout, token)` — it's cancellable and doesn't burn a thread. |

### If You Can't Go Fully Async

For sync-only code that you can't rewrite, wrap the cancellation check around the blocking call:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Poll with short timeout instead of indefinite block
        if (TryGetNextItem(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(500), out var item))
        {
            ProcessItem(item);
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check between steps
        }
    }
}
```

The core principle: **.NET 8 requires cooperative cancellation** — every long-running or blocking operation must periodically check the token or accept one as a parameter. There is no way to forcibly kill a thread.
